1. Update Theme.ets with the design-alignment color tokens (coral palette) — keeping the token API but updating values, plus add new tokens for the coral theme. Actually the design uses a coral/peach palette (#FF6B4A, #FFF8F0, etc.), totally different from the green template. The skill says "Keep Theme.ets as the shared semantic theme-token file" — I should update token VALUES to match the real design. I'll rewrite Theme with the coral tokens while preserving the layout contract tokens (pageHorizontalPadding, bottomTabHeight, contentMaxWidth, touchTarget) — though bottom tab height in design is 80, template is 68. I'll update bottomTabHeight to match design (80) since BottomTabBar uses Theme.bottomTabHeight. Actually changing layout contract tokens is allowed when "the app shell changes" — but the shell stays the same shape. I'll set bottomTabHeight to 80 to match the design's 80px tab bar. Let me keep it conservative: design says tab bar height 80px. I'll set 80.

2. Create the page files: Home, Fridge, Mood, Log pages + ShareCardSheet. Each is a component. Index.ets wires them with the 4 tabs + share-card overlay.

3. Update Index.ets to the new surface model: home/fridge/mood/log + share-card overlay.

4. Update main_pages.json? Pages are components, not entries — main_pages only has pages/Index (the @Entry). The other pages are @Component structs imported by Index. So main_pages stays as ["pages/Index"]. Good. Wait — the routes in ui-tree say pages/Home etc. But those are component files, not routable pages (no @Entry). The app uses single @Entry Index with surface switching (matches the scaffold shell pattern). So semantic "route" is conceptual; actual routing is via Index surface state. That's consistent with the scaffold shell contract. Good — keep main_pages as Index only.

Now, reactivity: controllers are plain classes with onChange callbacks. Pages need to re-render when controller state changes. In ArkUI V1 (@Component/@State), to re-render on plain object mutation, I need @State to hold a primitive that changes, or use @Observed. Simplest approach: each page holds @State version counter, registers as the controller's onChange, increments version on change, and reads controller fields directly in build. But @State reading controller.wheelState in build won't re-trigger unless a @State-tracked value changes. So increment a @State `tick` number and reference it in build (e.g., conditionally) to force re-render. Actually referencing this.tick in build is enough to register dependency.

Let me design pages with:
```
@Component
export struct HomePage {
  @State tick: number = 0;
  aboutToAppear() { homeController.onChange = () => { this.tick++; } }
  build() { ... reference this.tick somewhere ... }
